Scanning


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH, FTP, and HTTP. The FTP application allows anonymous login, so I will start enumeration there.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

Using anonymous login, I downloaded the two files that are available using the FTP on the target machine. These files are locks.txt and task.txt.


The contents of the two files are shown above. The first file locks.txt contains a list of possible passwords. The second file task.txt contains two usernames: vicious and lin.

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this HTTP application. I did not find anything useful when enumerating this application.

Exploitation



Using hydra, I bruteforced the SSH application with the usernames lin and vicious and passwords inside lock.txt. I did not get a hit for the user vicious; however, it worked for the user lin! Now I have the credential lin:RedDr4gonSynd1cat3. I have a foothold on the target machine now.

Privilege Escalation


Looks like the command /bin/tar can be executed as root to elevate privileges to root.


And entering the command sudo -u root tar -cf /dev/null /dev/null --checkpoint=1 --checkpoint-action=exec=/bin/sh, I gained a root shell. Now I have root access on the target machine.
